      "writtenOn": "2017-10-24T00:38:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e In order to validate that the builder really is part of that project, don\u0027t we still need to make an RPC call like this anyway for the time being?\n\u003e \n\u003e I can do (1), but then it\u0027s not really validating the bucket since someone could just put the project ID of the current project even though the builder is from a different project.\n\ndo\u0027h\n\n\u003e  Without an RPC call right now, there\u0027s no way to be sure someone isn\u0027t doing that. If buildbucket  emitted a project ID with the build information,\n\nit should be doing that, but currently does not\n\n\u003e  I could then just create builder ID as you suggest, and all would be fine.\n\u003e \n\u003e With (2) it\u0027s a little better since that can\u0027t happen, but it\u0027s not a good long-term solution and I agree will have to be replaced.\n\u003e \n\u003e I\u0027m not exactly sure what I should be doing now to get to a state where I can use luci-notify against prod buildbucket. What do you suggest? Just require project ID and don\u0027t fully validate (other than that it\u0027s there and the same as the current project)? Do (2) for now since its simple and then use project IDs later? Or should I just wait?\n\nI recommend (2), specifically, extract project id of a build from the \"luci.\u003cproject\u003e.\" prefix. And then read only notifiers of that project.\n\nI don\u0027t think we should support notifications for other projects. If a user needs a notification for another project, they should define a notifier in THAT project.\n\nStill, i think we it is better to not write validation code that prevents project x to specify luci.y.try in its config because eventually we will make bucket names unique only within the project, e.g. \"try\", not \"luci.fuchsia.try\"",
